[Category:Computational mathematics]]\n", "name_user": "Guillaume.bouchard", "label": "safe", "comment": "Optimal control is a very important topic in Control Theory, and the Reinforcement Learning wiki page links to it.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Control_theory"}
{"title_page": "Janowska concentration camp", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox concentration camp\n| name            = Janowska concentration camp\n| image           = Jewish prisoners forced to work for a Sonderkommando 1005 unit pose next to a bone crushing machine in the Janowska concentration camp.jpg\n| image size      = \n| type            = [[Concentration camp]]\n| caption         = Survivors of the camp's [[Sonderkommando 1005]] unit stand next to a bone crushing machine <small>(taken following the liberation of the camp in 1944)</small> \n| alt             = \n| location map    = Ukraine\n| map alt         = Ukraine\n| coordinates     = {{coord|49|51|15|N|23|59|24|E|region:UA_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n| map caption     = Location of Janowska camp in modern Ukraine\n{{location mark|float=center|image=WW2-Holocaust-Poland.PNG |width=226 |x%=69.5 |y%=74.4 |label='''Janowska''' |position=right}}\nLocation of KL Janowska in World War&nbsp;II,<br />south of the [[Belzec]] [[death camp]]\n| location        = Lemberg, [[District of Galicia]], [[General Government]] (formerly Lw\u00f3w, [[Second Polish Republic]]; today [[Lviv]], Ukraine)\n| operated by     = [[SS]]\n| original use    = \n| construction    = \n| in operation    = September 1941 \u2013 November 1943\n| prisoner type   = Jews\n| inmates         = 100,000\n| killed          = 35,000\u201340,000\n| liberated by    = The Red Army\n| notable inmates = \n| notable books   = \n| website         = {{URL|https://encyclopedia.ushmm.org/content/en/article/janowska}}\n}}\n'''Janowska concentration camp''' ({{lang-pl|Janowska}}, {{lang-ru|\u042f\u043d\u043e\u0432 or \"Yanov\"}}, {{lang-uk|\u042f\u043d\u0456\u0432\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0442\u0430\u0431\u0456\u0440}}) was a [[Nazi concentration camp]] combining elements of labor, transit and [[extermination camp]]s. It was established in September 1941 on the outskirts of Lw\u00f3w in [[Eastern Poland]] / [[Western Ukraine]] (today: [[Lviv]], Ukraine). The camp was named after the nearby street ''Janowska'' in Lw\u00f3w of the interwar [[Second Polish Republic]]. The camp was liquidated in November 1943, with the evidence of mass murder being largely destroyed in the Nazi program of ''[[Sonderaktion 1005]]''. Estimates put the total number of prisoners who passed through the Janowska camp at between 100,000 and 120,000, mostly Polish and Soviet Jews.<ref name=Kerenji>{{cite book |title=Jewish Responses to Persecution: 1942\u20131943 |author=Emil Kerenji |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gXDYBAAAQBAJ&q=Janowska+100%2C000+DAW |year=2014 |isbn=978-1442236271 |pages=69\u201370, 539}}</ref> The number of victims murdered at the camp is estimated at 35,000\u201340,000.\n\n==Background==\n{{Main|Lviv pogroms (1941)}}\nLw\u00f3w ([[Lviv]]) was a multicultural city just before World War&nbsp;II, with a population of 312,231. The city's 157,490 ethnic Poles constituted just over 50 per cent, with Jews at 32 per cent (99,595) and Ukrainians at 16 per cent (49,747).{{sfn|Himka|2011|p=210}} On 28 September 1939, after the [[Invasion of Poland|joint Soviet-German invasion]], the [[USSR]] and [[Nazi Germany]] signed the [[German\u2013Soviet Frontier Treaty]], which assigned about 200,000&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> (77,000&nbsp;sq&nbsp;mi) of Polish territory inhabited by 13.5&nbsp;million people of all nationalities to the Soviet Union. Lviv was then [[Territories of Poland annexed by the Soviet Union|annexed to the Soviet Union]] as part of the [[Ukrainian SSR]].{{sfn|Gross|2002 |pages=[https://books.google.com/books?id=XKtOr4EXOWwC&pg=PA17 17, 28\u201330]}}\n\nAt the time of the German attack on the Soviet Union in June 1941, about 160,000 Jews lived in the city;{{sfn|Beorn|2018|p=136}} the number had swelled by tens of thousands due to the arrival of Jewish refugees from German-occupied Poland in late 1939.{{sfn|Kulke|2012|p=802}} Lviv was occupied by the [[Wehrmacht]] on 30 June 1941. Jews were press-ganged by the Germans to remove bodies of the victims of the [[NKVD prisoner massacre]]s for which [[Nazi propaganda]] and Ukrainian nationalists blamed the Jews.{{sfn|Himka|2011|p=211}} In the ensuing [[Lviv pogroms (1941)|July pogroms]] and the concurrent [[Einsatzgruppen]] killings, thousands of Jews were murdered.{{sfn|Kulke|2012|p=802}}\n\n==Lw\u00f3w Ghetto==\n{{main|Lw\u00f3w Ghetto}}\nIn early November 1941, the Nazis closed-off northern portions of the city thus forming the [[Lw\u00f3w Ghetto]].<ref name=\"Koonz\">{{cite journal |url=http://www.uvm.edu/~uvmchs/documents/KoonzHilbergLecture_002.pdf |title=SS Man Katzmann's \"Solution of the Jewish Question in the District of Galicia\" |publisher=University of Vermont |journal=The Raul Hilberg Lecture |date=November 2, 2005 |accessdate=January 30, 2015 |author=Claudia Koonz |pages=2, 11, 16\u201318 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150205021305/http://www.uvm.edu/~uvmchs/documents/KoonzHilbergLecture_002.pdf |archive-date=February 5, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> During the forced relocation of the Jewish families to the newly created ghetto, German police shot and killed thousands of elderly and sick Jews as they crossed under the rail bridge on Pe\u0142tewna Street (which came to be known as the ''bridge of death'' for the Jews). Several months later, in March 1942, the Nazi police under [[Fritz Katzmann]] began to deport Jews from the ghetto to the [[Belzec extermination camp]]. By August 1942, more than 65,000 Jews from Lw\u00f3w had been sent away aboard [[Holocaust trains]] and killed. In early June 1943, the Germans destroyed and liquidated the ghetto.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">Filip Friedman, ''Zag\u0142ada \u017byd\u00f3w lwowskich'' (Extermination of the Jews of Lw\u00f3w) {{OCLC|38706656}}.</ref>\n\n==Labour and transit camp==\nIn addition to the Lw\u00f3w ghetto, in September 1941 the occupation authorities set up a German Armament Works D.A.W. factory (''[[Deutsche Ausr\u00fcstungswerke]]'') in prewar Steinhaus Milling Machines Merchants (''Maszyny m\u0142y\u0144skie - Sprzeda\u017c'') on 134 Janowska Street (Grodecka 10a address),<ref>Jewishgen.org (May 2005), [https://kehilalinks.jewishgen.org/lviv/FramesetSt.html Businesses, Partnerships and Addresses: Steinhaus Milling Machines-Merchants]</ref> in northwestern suburbs of Lw\u00f3w. This factory became a part of a network of factories owned and operated by the SS. The commandant of the camp was ''{{nobreak|SS-Haupsturmf\u00fchrer}}'' Fritz Gebauer. Jews who worked at this factory were used as forced laborers, mainly working in [[carpentry]] and [[metalwork]].\n\nIn October 1941, the Nazis established a concentration camp next to the factory, which housed the forced laborers along with other prisoners. Thousands of Jews from the Lw\u00f3w ghetto were forced to work as [[Slavery|slave]] laborers in this complex. When the Lw\u00f3w ghetto was liquidated by the Nazis, the ghetto's inhabitants who were fit for work were sent to the Janowska camp; the rest were deported to [[Belzec]] for extermination. The concentration camp was guarded by a ''[[Sonderdienst]]'' battalion of the {{nobreak|''SS''-trained}} ''[[Hiwi (volunteer)|Hiwi]]'' guards known as \"[[Trawniki men]]\".<ref name=USHMM1>{{cite web |url=http://www.ushmm.org/wlc/en/article.php?ModuleId=10007397 |title=Trawniki |publisher=United States Holocaust Memorial Museum |author=Holocaust Encyclopedia |accessdate=July 21, 2011 |id=permission granted to be reused, in whole or in part, on Wikipedia; [[OTRS]] ticket no. 2007071910012533 |quote=Text from USHMM has been released under the [[GFDL]].}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to being a forced-labor camp for Jews, Janowska was a transit camp (''Durchgangslager Janowska'') during the [[Final Solution|mass deportations of Polish Jews to the killing centers]] from across German-occupied southeastern Poland (now western Ukraine) in 1942. Jews underwent a selection process in Janowska camp similar to that used at [[Auschwitz-Birkenau|Auschwitz\u2013Birkenau]] and [[Majdanek]] [[extermination camps]]. Those classified as fit to work remained at Janowska for forced labor. The majority, rejected as unfit for work, were deported to Belzec and killed, or else were shot at the Piaski ravine, located just north of the camp. In the summer and fall of 1942, thousands of Jews (mainly from the Lw\u00f3w ghetto) were deported to Janowska and killed in the Piaski ravine.{{cn|date=February 2020}}\n\nThe Nazis occasionally allowed small groups of Jews to go to town for daylong leaves of absence.  They would use this temporary freedom to dig up [[Torah]]s that had been hidden in Lw\u00f3w's Jewish cemetery.  The Torahs were then cut into pieces which were hidden under their clothes and smuggled back into the camp.  After the war the various pieces were assembled into a single scroll, the [[Yanov torah]], which is currently in California.<ref>Erwin and Agnes Herman ''The Yanov Torah'' [[Kar-Ben Publishing]] {{ISBN|978-0930494452}} (1985)</ref>\n\n==Liquidation==\n[[File:Site of Janowska Nazi Camp - Lviv, 1944.jpg|thumbnail|right|Soviet [[Extraordinary State Commission]] at the site of mass graves adjoining the camp, 1944.]]\nAhead of the Soviet advance, in November 1943 the new camp commandant ''SS-Hauptsturmf\u00fchrer'' Friedrich Warzok was put in charge of the evacuation of the Janowska inmates to [[Przemy\u015bl]].<ref name=\"Levy\">{{cite book | last = Levy | first = Alan | authorlink = Alan Levy | title = Nazi Hunter: The Wiesenthal File | edition = Revised 2002 | year = 2006 | origyear = 1993 | publisher = Constable & Robinson | location = London | isbn = 978-1-84119-607-7 | ref = harv }}</ref> The Germans attempted to destroy the traces of mass murder during ''[[Sonderaktion 1005]]''. Prisoners were forced to open the mass graves in Lesienicki forest and burn the bodies. On November 19, 1943, the ''Sonderkommando'' inmates staged a revolt against the Nazis and attempted a mass escape. A few succeeded, but most were recaptured and killed. The SS and their local auxiliaries murdered at least 6,000 Jews who had survived the uprising killings at Janowska, as well as Jews in other forced labor camps in [[Galicia (Eastern Europe)|Galicia]], at the time of the camps' liquidation.<ref>{{cite web|author=USHMM |url=https://encyclopedia.ushmm.org/content/en/article/janowska |title=Janowska| encyclopedia=[[Holocaust Encyclopedia]] |publisher=United States Holocaust Memorial Museum |accessdate=2018-11-18 |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe Soviet [[Extraordinary State Commission]] determined that over 200,000 people were killed in Janowska in the course of the camp operation. The ashes mixed with crushed bones were buried to a depth of six feet in various places.<ref name=\"HEART\" /> {{Interlanguage link multi|Leon Weliczker Wells|de}} told the Commission that between June 6 and November 20, 1943 his \"team burned more than 310,000 bodies\" including 170,000 in the immediate vicinity of the camp and another 140,000 or more in the Lysynychi area of eastern Lw\u00f3w.<ref>[[Avner Falk]] ''Anti-semitism: A History and Psychoanalysis of Contemporary Hatred'' [[ABC-CLIO]] {{ISBN|9780313353840}} (2008) p. 191</ref>  Weliczker repeated the claim of \"a few hundred thousand\" at [[Adolf Eichmann]]'s trial in 1961.<ref>[http://www.nizkor.org/hweb/people/e/eichmann-adolf/transcripts/Sessions/Session-023-03.html \"The Trial of Adolf Eichmann\"] Session #23 2 May 1961</ref> Weliczker also described his work as part of the Sonderaktion 1005 in his book ''Death Brigade''.\n\nJanowska served as a Soviet prison camp after its liberation.<ref name=\"HEART\">{{cite web | url=http://www.holocaustresearchproject.org/othercamps/janowska.html | title=The Soviet Special Commission | publisher=Holocaust Education & Archive Research Team | work=Janowska \u2013 Lvov | year=2007 | accessdate=January 28, 2018 | author=Carmelo Lisciotto, H.E.A.R.T}}</ref><br />\n\n==Tango of Death==\n[[File:Janowska Nazi camp orchestra.jpg|thumb|Tango of Death]]\nIn the Janowska concentration camp, the Nazis conducted torture and executions to music. The Orchestra members, who were prisoners, played one and the same tune, Tango of Death. Lviv National Philharmonic Orchestra professor Shtriks, opera conductor Mund and other famous Jewish musicians were among the members. \n\nDuring hanging the Nazis ordered the orchestra to play tango, and during tortures the musicians had to play foxtrot. Some evenings the orchestra musicians were made to play under the camp commander\u2019s windows for hours on end.\n\nOn the eve of Lviv\u2019s liberation German Nazis ordered 40 orchestra musicians to form a circle. The security ringed the musicians tightly and ordered them to play. First the orchestra conductor, Mund, was executed. Then the commandant ordered the musicians to come to the center of the circle one by one, put their instrument onto the ground and strip naked, after which they were killed by a headshot.\n\nA photo of the orchestra players was one of the incriminating documents at the [[Nuremberg trials]].\n\nJacob Mund\u2019s story is described in the book called [https://www.amazon.com/Tango-Death-Story-Holocaust-Survivors/dp/B085HHMGMT/ Tango of Death].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://awesomegang.com/tango-of-death-a-true-story-of-a-holocaust-survivor/|title=Tango of Death: A True Story of a Holocaust Survivor|last=O'Hare|first=Vinny|website=awesomegang.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n==Notable inmates==<!-- Please respect alphabetical order -->\n* [[Maurycy Allerhand]], lawyer\n* [[Adolf Beck (physiologist)|Adolf Beck]], physiologist\n* [[Enrico Ciantelli]] Italian Military Internee, lawyer\n* [[Janina Altman|Janina Hescheles]] (then Altman), Polish-Israeli chemist and writer \n* Rabbi [[Yisroel Spira]], Grand Rabbi of Bluzev ([[B\u0142a\u017cowa]])\n* [[Emanuel Szlechter]], screenwriter and lyricist\n* [[William Ungar]], founder of the [[National Envelope Corporation]]\n* [[Debora Vogel]], philosopher and poet\n* [[Simon Wiesenthal]], [[Nazi hunter]]\n\n==See also==\n{{div col|colwidth=21em}}\n* [[Kaiser Wilhelm Institute of Anthropology, Human Heredity, and Eugenics]]\n* [[List of Nazi concentration camps]]\n* [[Nazi concentration camps]]\n{{div col end}}\n{{Portal bar|Genocide|Germany|Poland|World War II}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}} \n*[https://www.amazon.com/Tango-Death-Story-Holocaust-Survivors/dp/B085HHMGMT/ Tango of Death]. A True Story of Holocaust Survivors \u2014 Mr. Mintz Publishing, Mikhail Baranovskiy, 2020. - ISBN 979-8620147014\n*{{cite book |last1=Beorn |first1=Waitman Wade |author-link = Waitman Wade Beorn|title=The Holocaust in Eastern Europe: At the Epicenter of the Final Solution |date=2018 |publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing |isbn=978-1474232227 |ref = harv}}\n* Filip Friedman, ''Zag\u0142ada \u017byd\u00f3w Lwowskich'' (Extermination of the Jews of Lw\u00f3w) \u2013 [https://web.archive.org/web/20101106061357/http://www.mankurty.com/fridpl.html online in Polish, Ukrainian and Russian]\n*{{cite book |authorlink=Jan T. Gross |last=Gross |first=Jan Tomasz |year=2002 |title=Revolution from Abroad: The Soviet Conquest of Poland's Western Ukraine and Western Belorussia |location=Princeton, [[New Jersey|NJ]] |publisher=Princeton University Press |isbn=0691096031 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal |last=Himka |first=John-Paul |author-link =John-Paul Himka | year=2011 |title=The Lviv Pogrom of 1941: The Germans, Ukrainian Nationalists, and the Carnival Crowd |journal=[[Canadian Slavonic Papers]] |volume=53 |issue=2\u20134 |pages=209\u2013243 |issn=0008-5006 |id=Taylor & Francis |doi=10.1080/00085006.2011.11092673|ref=harv |url=https://www.academia.edu/3181252}}\n*{{cite encyclopedia| first=Christine  |last=Kulke |editor1=[[Geoffrey P. Megargee]] |title=Lw\u00f3w |encyclopedia=[[Encyclopedia of Camps and Ghettos, 1933\u20131945]]. Ghettos in German-Occupied Eastern Europe |publisher=The United States Holocaust Memorial Museum |year=2012 |volume=II, part A |isbn=978-0-253-00202-0 |ref=harv}}\n* Aharon Weiss, [[Encyclopaedia of the Holocaust]] (Hebrew edition), vol. 3, pp.&nbsp;572\u2013575. Map, illustration\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Janowska Nazi camp}}\n* [http://www.ushmm.org/ US Holocaust Memorial Museum Website (Search: \"Janowska\")]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120214102219/http://www.nizkor.org/hweb/people/e/eichmann-adolf/transcripts/Sessions/Session-022-02.html Eichmann Trial transcript: Testimony of Dr. Leon Weliczker-Wells (part 1 of 5)] \u2013 navigate consecutive web pages within website\n* [http://www.history.ucsb.edu/projects/holocaust/ Story of Nina Morecki], who was imprisoned in Janowska in 1942; photo page has images of boulder memorial at site of mass executions\n* [http://www.holocaustresearchproject.org/othercamps/janowska.html The HolocaustResesearchProject]\n\n{{Holocaust Poland}} \n{{Prison riots and uprisings}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1941 establishments in Ukraine]]\n[[Category:1942 in Ukraine]]\n[[Category:1943 disestablishments]]\n[[Category:1943 in Ukraine]]\n[[Category:1943 riots]]\n[[Category:Nazi concentration camps in Ukraine]]\n[[Category:Prison uprisings]]\n[[Category:General Government]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox concentration camp\n| name            = Janowska concentration camp\n| image           = Jewish prisoners forced to work for a Sonderkommando 1005 unit pose next to a bone crushing machine in the Janowska concentration camp.jpg\n| image size      = \n| type            = [[Concentration camp]]\n| caption         = Survivors of the camp's [[Sonderkommando 1005]] unit stand next to a bone crushing machine <small>(taken following the liberation of the camp in 1944)</small> \n| alt             = \n| location map    = Ukraine\n| map alt         = Ukraine\n| coordinates     = {{coord|49|51|15|N|23|59|24|E|region:UA_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n| map caption     = Location of Janowska camp in modern Ukraine\n{{location mark|float=center|image=WW2-Holocaust-Poland.PNG |width=226 |x%=69.5 |y%=74.4 |label='''Janowska''' |position=right}}\nLocation of KL Janowska in World War&nbsp;II,<br />south of the [[Belzec]] [[death camp]]\n| location        = Lemberg, [[District of Galicia]], [[General Government]] (formerly Lw\u00f3w, [[Second Polish Republic]]; today [[Lviv]], Ukraine)\n| operated by     = [[SS]]\n| original use    = \n| construction    = \n| in operation    = September 1941 \u2013 November 1943\n| prisoner type   = Jews\n| inmates         = 100,000\n| killed          = 35,000\u201340,000\n| liberated by    = The Red Army\n| notable inmates = \n| notable books   = \n| website         = {{URL|https://encyclopedia.ushmm.org/content/en/article/janowska}}\n}}\n'''Janowska concentration camp''' ({{lang-pl|Janowska}}, {{lang-ru|\u042f\u043d\u043e\u0432 or \"Yanov\"}}, {{lang-uk|\u042f\u043d\u0456\u0432\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0442\u0430\u0431\u0456\u0440}}) was a [[Nazi concentration camp]] combining elements of labor, transit and [[extermination camp]]s. It was established in September 1941 on the outskirts of Lw\u00f3w in [[Eastern Poland]] / [[Western Ukraine]] (today: [[Lviv]], Ukraine). The camp was named after the nearby street ''Janowska'' in Lw\u00f3w of the interwar [[Second Polish Republic]]. The camp was liquidated in November 1943, with the evidence of mass murder being largely destroyed in the Nazi program of ''[[Sonderaktion 1005]]''. Estimates put the total number of prisoners who passed through the Janowska camp at between 100,000 and 120,000, mostly Polish and Soviet Jews.<ref name=Kerenji>{{cite book |title=Jewish Responses to Persecution: 1942\u20131943 |author=Emil Kerenji |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gXDYBAAAQBAJ&q=Janowska+100%2C000+DAW |year=2014 |isbn=978-1442236271 |pages=69\u201370, 539}}</ref> The number of victims murdered at the camp is estimated at 35,000\u201340,000.\n\n==Background==\n{{Main|Lviv pogroms (1941)}}\nLw\u00f3w ([[Lviv]]) was a multicultural city just before World War&nbsp;II, with a population of 312,231. The city's 157,490 ethnic Poles constituted just over 50 per cent, with Jews at 32 per cent (99,595) and Ukrainians at 16 per cent (49,747).{{sfn|Himka|2011|p=210}} On 28 September 1939, after the [[Invasion of Poland|joint Soviet-German invasion]], the [[USSR]] and [[Nazi Germany]] signed the [[German\u2013Soviet Frontier Treaty]], which assigned about 200,000&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> (77,000&nbsp;sq&nbsp;mi) of Polish territory inhabited by 13.5&nbsp;million people of all nationalities to the Soviet Union. Lviv was then [[Territories of Poland annexed by the Soviet Union|annexed to the Soviet Union]] as part of the [[Ukrainian SSR]].{{sfn|Gross|2002 |pages=[https://books.google.com/books?id=XKtOr4EXOWwC&pg=PA17 17, 28\u201330]}}\n\nAt the time of the German attack on the Soviet Union in June 1941, about 160,000 Jews lived in the city;{{sfn|Beorn|2018|p=136}} the number had swelled by tens of thousands due to the arrival of Jewish refugees from German-occupied Poland in late 1939.{{sfn|Kulke|2012|p=802}} Lviv was occupied by the [[Wehrmacht]] on 30 June 1941. Jews were press-ganged by the Germans to remove bodies of the victims of the [[NKVD prisoner massacre]]s for which [[Nazi propaganda]] and Ukrainian nationalists blamed the Jews.{{sfn|Himka|2011|p=211}} In the ensuing [[Lviv pogroms (1941)|July pogroms]] and the concurrent [[Einsatzgruppen]] killings, thousands of Jews were murdered.{{sfn|Kulke|2012|p=802}}\n\n==Lw\u00f3w Ghetto==\n{{main|Lw\u00f3w Ghetto}}\nIn early November 1941, the Nazis closed-off northern portions of the city thus forming the [[Lw\u00f3w Ghetto]].<ref name=\"Koonz\">{{cite journal |url=http://www.uvm.edu/~uvmchs/documents/KoonzHilbergLecture_002.pdf |title=SS Man Katzmann's \"Solution of the Jewish Question in the District of Galicia\" |publisher=University of Vermont |journal=The Raul Hilberg Lecture |date=November 2, 2005 |accessdate=January 30, 2015 |author=Claudia Koonz |pages=2, 11, 16\u201318 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150205021305/http://www.uvm.edu/~uvmchs/documents/KoonzHilbergLecture_002.pdf |archive-date=February 5, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> During the forced relocation of the Jewish families to the newly created ghetto, German police shot and killed thousands of elderly and sick Jews as they crossed under the rail bridge on Pe\u0142tewna Street (which came to be known as the ''bridge of death'' for the Jews). Several months later, in March 1942, the Nazi police under [[Fritz Katzmann]] began to deport Jews from the ghetto to the [[Belzec extermination camp]]. By August 1942, more than 65,000 Jews from Lw\u00f3w had been sent away aboard [[Holocaust trains]] and killed. In early June 1943, the Germans destroyed and liquidated the ghetto.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">Filip Friedman, ''Zag\u0142ada \u017byd\u00f3w lwowskich'' (Extermination of the Jews of Lw\u00f3w) {{OCLC|38706656}}.</ref>\n\n==Labour and transit camp==\nIn addition to the Lw\u00f3w ghetto, in September 1941 the occupation authorities set up a German Armament Works D.A.W. factory (''[[Deutsche Ausr\u00fcstungswerke]]'') in prewar Steinhaus Milling Machines Merchants (''Maszyny m\u0142y\u0144skie - Sprzeda\u017c'') on 134 Janowska Street (Grodecka 10a address),<ref>Jewishgen.org (May 2005), [https://kehilalinks.jewishgen.org/lviv/FramesetSt.html Businesses, Partnerships and Addresses: Steinhaus Milling Machines-Merchants]</ref> in northwestern suburbs of Lw\u00f3w. This factory became a part of a network of factories owned and operated by the SS. The commandant of the camp was ''{{nobreak|SS-Haupsturmf\u00fchrer}}'' Fritz Gebauer. Jews who worked at this factory were used as forced laborers, mainly working in [[carpentry]] and [[metalwork]].\n\nIn October 1941, the Nazis established a concentration camp next to the factory, which housed the forced laborers along with other prisoners. Thousands of Jews from the Lw\u00f3w ghetto were forced to work as [[Slavery|slave]] laborers in this complex. When the Lw\u00f3w ghetto was liquidated by the Nazis, the ghetto's inhabitants who were fit for work were sent to the Janowska camp; the rest were deported to [[Belzec]] for extermination. The concentration camp was guarded by a ''[[Sonderdienst]]'' battalion of the {{nobreak|''SS''-trained}} ''[[Hiwi (volunteer)|Hiwi]]'' guards known as \"[[Trawniki men]]\".<ref name=USHMM1>{{cite web |url=http://www.ushmm.org/wlc/en/article.php?ModuleId=10007397 |title=Trawniki |publisher=United States Holocaust Memorial Museum |author=Holocaust Encyclopedia |accessdate=July 21, 2011 |id=permission granted to be reused, in whole or in part, on Wikipedia; [[OTRS]] ticket no. 2007071910012533 |quote=Text from USHMM has been released under the [[GFDL]].}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to being a forced-labor camp for Jews, Janowska was a transit camp (''Durchgangslager Janowska'') during the [[Final Solution|mass deportations of Polish Jews to the killing centers]] from across German-occupied southeastern Poland (now western Ukraine) in 1942. Jews underwent a selection process in Janowska camp similar to that used at [[Auschwitz-Birkenau|Auschwitz\u2013Birkenau]] and [[Majdanek]] [[extermination camps]]. Those classified as fit to work remained at Janowska for forced labor. The majority, rejected as unfit for work, were deported to Belzec and killed, or else were shot at the Piaski ravine, located just north of the camp. In the summer and fall of 1942, thousands of Jews (mainly from the Lw\u00f3w ghetto) were deported to Janowska and killed in the Piaski ravine.{{cn|date=February 2020}}\n\nThe Nazis occasionally allowed small groups of Jews to go to town for daylong leaves of absence.  They would use this temporary freedom to dig up [[Torah]]s that had been hidden in Lw\u00f3w's Jewish cemetery.  The Torahs were then cut into pieces which were hidden under their clothes and smuggled back into the camp.  After the war the various pieces were assembled into a single scroll, the [[Yanov torah]], which is currently in California.<ref>Erwin and Agnes Herman ''The Yanov Torah'' [[Kar-Ben Publishing]] {{ISBN|978-0930494452}} (1985)</ref>\n\n==Liquidation==\n[[File:Site of Janowska Nazi Camp - Lviv, 1944.jpg|thumbnail|right|Soviet [[Extraordinary State Commission]] at the site of mass graves adjoining the camp, 1944.]]\nAhead of the Soviet advance, in November 1943 the new camp commandant ''SS-Hauptsturmf\u00fchrer'' Friedrich Warzok was put in charge of the evacuation of the Janowska inmates to [[Przemy\u015bl]].<ref name=\"Levy\">{{cite book | last = Levy | first = Alan | authorlink = Alan Levy | title = Nazi Hunter: The Wiesenthal File | edition = Revised 2002 | year = 2006 | origyear = 1993 | publisher = Constable & Robinson | location = London | isbn = 978-1-84119-607-7 | ref = harv }}</ref> The Germans attempted to destroy the traces of mass murder during ''[[Sonderaktion 1005]]''. Prisoners were forced to open the mass graves in Lesienicki forest and burn the bodies. On November 19, 1943, the ''Sonderkommando'' inmates staged a revolt against the Nazis and attempted a mass escape. A few succeeded, but most were recaptured and killed. The SS and their local auxiliaries murdered at least 6,000 Jews who had survived the uprising killings at Janowska, as well as Jews in other forced labor camps in [[Galicia (Eastern Europe)|Galicia]], at the time of the camps' liquidation.<ref>{{cite web|author=USHMM |url=https://encyclopedia.ushmm.org/content/en/article/janowska |title=Janowska| encyclopedia=[[Holocaust Encyclopedia]] |publisher=United States Holocaust Memorial Museum |accessdate=2018-11-18 |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe Soviet [[Extraordinary State Commission]] determined that over 200,000 people were killed in Janowska in the course of the camp operation. The ashes mixed with crushed bones were buried to a depth of six feet in various places.<ref name=\"HEART\" /> {{Interlanguage link multi|Leon Weliczker Wells|de}} told the Commission that between June 6 and November 20, 1943 his \"team burned more than 310,000 bodies\" including 170,000 in the immediate vicinity of the camp and another 140,000 or more in the Lysynychi area of eastern Lw\u00f3w.<ref>[[Avner Falk]] ''Anti-semitism: A History and Psychoanalysis of Contemporary Hatred'' [[ABC-CLIO]] {{ISBN|9780313353840}} (2008) p. 191</ref>  Weliczker repeated the claim of \"a few hundred thousand\" at [[Adolf Eichmann]]'s trial in 1961.<ref>[http://www.nizkor.org/hweb/people/e/eichmann-adolf/transcripts/Sessions/Session-023-03.html \"The Trial of Adolf Eichmann\"] Session #23 2 May 1961</ref> Weliczker also described his work as part of the Sonderaktion 1005 in his book ''Death Brigade''.\n\nJanowska served as a Soviet prison camp after its liberation.<ref name=\"HEART\">{{cite web | url=http://www.holocaustresearchproject.org/othercamps/janowska.html | title=The Soviet Special Commission | publisher=Holocaust Education & Archive Research Team | work=Janowska \u2013 Lvov | year=2007 | accessdate=January 28, 2018 | author=Carmelo Lisciotto, H.E.A.R.T}}</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n==Tango of Death==\n[[File:Janowska Nazi camp orchestra.jpg|thumb|Tango of Death]]\nIn the Janowska concentration camp, the Nazis conducted torture and executions to music. The Orchestra members, who were prisoners, played one and the same tune, Tango of Death. Lviv National Philharmonic Orchestra professor Shtriks, opera conductor Mund and other famous Jewish musicians were among the members. \n\nDuring hanging the Nazis ordered the orchestra to play tango, and during tortures the musicians had to play foxtrot. Some evenings the orchestra musicians were made to play under the camp commander\u2019s windows for hours on end.\n\nOn the eve of Lviv\u2019s liberation German Nazis ordered 40 orchestra musicians to form a circle. The security ringed the musicians tightly and ordered them to play. First the orchestra conductor, Mund, was executed. Then the commandant ordered the musicians to come to the center of the circle one by one, put their instrument onto the ground and strip naked, after which they were killed by a headshot.\n\nA photo of the orchestra players was one of the incriminating documents at the [[Nuremberg trials]].\n\nJacob Mund\u2019s story is described in the book called [https://www.amazon.com/Tango-Death-Story-Holocaust-Survivors/dp/B085HHMGMT/ Tango of Death].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://awesomegang.com/tango-of-death-a-true-story-of-a-holocaust-survivor/|title=Tango of Death: A True Story of a Holocaust Survivor|last=O'Hare|first=Vinny|website=awesomegang.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n==Notable inmates==<!-- Please respect alphabetical order -->\n* [[Maurycy Allerhand]], lawyer\n* [[Adolf Beck (physiologist)|Adolf Beck]], physiologist\n* [[Enrico Ciantelli]] Italian Military Internee, lawyer\n* [[Janina Altman|Janina Hescheles]] (then Altman), Polish-Israeli chemist and writer \n* Rabbi [[Yisroel Spira]], Grand Rabbi of Bluzev ([[B\u0142a\u017cowa]])\n* [[Emanuel Szlechter]], screenwriter and lyricist\n* [[William Ungar]], founder of the [[National Envelope Corporation]]\n* [[Debora Vogel]], philosopher and poet\n* [[Simon Wiesenthal]], [[Nazi hunter]]\n\n==See also==\n{{div col|colwidth=21em}}\n* [[Kaiser Wilhelm Institute of Anthropology, Human Heredity, and Eugenics]]\n* [[List of Nazi concentration camps]]\n* [[Nazi concentration camps]]\n{{div col end}}\n{{Portal bar|Genocide|Germany|Poland|World War II}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}} \n*[https://www.amazon.com/Tango-Death-Story-Holocaust-Survivors/dp/B085HHMGMT/ Tango of Death]. A True Story of Holocaust Survivors \u2014 Mr. Mintz Publishing, Mikhail Baranovskiy, 2020. - ISBN 979-8620147014\n*{{cite book |last1=Beorn |first1=Waitman Wade |author-link = Waitman Wade Beorn|title=The Holocaust in Eastern Europe: At the Epicenter of the Final Solution |date=2018 |publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing |isbn=978-1474232227 |ref = harv}}\n* Filip Friedman, ''Zag\u0142ada \u017byd\u00f3w Lwowskich'' (Extermination of the Jews of Lw\u00f3w) \u2013 [https://web.archive.org/web/20101106061357/http://www.mankurty.com/fridpl.html online in Polish, Ukrainian and Russian]\n*{{cite book |authorlink=Jan T. Gross |last=Gross |first=Jan Tomasz |year=2002 |title=Revolution from Abroad: The Soviet Conquest of Poland's Western Ukraine and Western Belorussia |location=Princeton, [[New Jersey|NJ]] |publisher=Princeton University Press |isbn=0691096031 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal |last=Himka |first=John-Paul |author-link =John-Paul Himka | year=2011 |title=The Lviv Pogrom of 1941: The Germans, Ukrainian Nationalists, and the Carnival Crowd |journal=[[Canadian Slavonic Papers]] |volume=53 |issue=2\u20134 |pages=209\u2013243 |issn=0008-5006 |id=Taylor & Francis |doi=10.1080/00085006.2011.11092673|ref=harv |url=https://www.academia.edu/3181252}}\n*{{cite encyclopedia| first=Christine  |last=Kulke |editor1=[[Geoffrey P. Megargee]] |title=Lw\u00f3w |encyclopedia=[[Encyclopedia of Camps and Ghettos, 1933\u20131945]]. Ghettos in German-Occupied Eastern Europe |publisher=The United States Holocaust Memorial Museum |year=2012 |volume=II, part A |isbn=978-0-253-00202-0 |ref=harv}}\n* Aharon Weiss, [[Encyclopaedia of the Holocaust]] (Hebrew edition), vol. 3, pp.&nbsp;572\u2013575. Map, illustration\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Janowska Nazi camp}}\n* [http://www.ushmm.org/ US Holocaust Memorial Museum Website (Search: \"Janowska\")]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120214102219/http://www.nizkor.org/hweb/people/e/eichmann-adolf/transcripts/Sessions/Session-022-02.html Eichmann Trial transcript: Testimony of Dr. Leon Weliczker-Wells (part 1 of 5)] \u2013 navigate consecutive web pages within website\n* [http://www.history.ucsb.edu/projects/holocaust/ Story of Nina Morecki], who was imprisoned in Janowska in 1942; photo page has images of boulder memorial at site of mass executions\n* [http://www.holocaustresearchproject.org/othercamps/janowska.html The HolocaustResesearchProject]\n\n{{Holocaust Poland}} \n{{Prison riots and uprisings}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1941 establishments in Ukraine]]\n[[Category:1942 in Ukraine]]\n[[Category:1943 disestablishments]]\n[[Category:1943 in Ukraine]]\n[[Category:1943 riots]]\n[[Category:Nazi concentration camps in Ukraine]]\n[[Category:Prison uprisings]]\n[[Category:General Government]]\n", "name_user": "Deepcom", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Janowska_concentration_camp"}
{"title_page": "Bernie Finn", "text_new": "{{for|the football player|Bernie Finn (American football)}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2014}}\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name               = Bernie Finn\n|honorific-suffix   = MLC\n|image              = \n|birth_name         = Bernard Thomas Christopher Finn\n|birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1961|4|14|df=y}}\n|birth_place        = \n|office1            = Member of the [[Victorian Legislative Council]]\n|party              = [[Liberal Party of Australia (Victorian Division)|Liberal Party]]\n|occupation         = Businessman, broadcaster, ministerial advisor\n<!-- Deprecated parameter |religion = [[Roman Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]] -->\n|term_start1        = 25 November 2006\n|website            = {{url|http://www.berniefinn.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Bernard (Bernie) Thomas Christopher Finn''' (born 14 April 1961) is a member of the [[Victorian Legislative Council]] representing the [[Western Metropolitan Region]] since the election of November 2006.<ref name=parlbio>{{cite web |title=Bernie Finn (Western Metropolitan)|work=Members Information |publisher=[[Parliament of Victoria]]|url=http://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/members/id/28|accessdate=20 December 2011}}</ref> He was previously the member for the [[electoral district of Tullamarine]] in the [[Victorian Legislative Assembly]] from October 1992 until September 1999.\n\n==Political career==\nFinn was originally a member of the [[Democratic Labour Party (Australia)|Democratic Labor Party]] (DLP). In 1980, aged 19, he was the DLP candidate for the federal seat of [[Division of Corangamite|Corangamite]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://psephos.adam-carr.net/countries/a/australia/1980/1980repsvic.txt|title=1980 Election|website=Psephos|last=Carr|first=Adam}}</ref> Soon after, he left the DLP and joined the [[Liberal Party of Australia (Victorian Division)|Liberal Party]]. In 1983 he was the Liberal candidate for the seat of [[Division of Burke (1969\u20132004)|Burke]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://psephos.adam-carr.net/countries/a/australia/1983/1983repsvic.txt|title=1983 Election|last=Carr|first=Adam|website=Psephos}}</ref>\n\nFinn was the Member for the District of Tullamarine from 1992 until 1999 when he lost power in the Steve Bracks led landslide victory over the Kennett Liberal Government.\n\nFinn has been the number one candidate on the Liberal Party of Australia ticket in the Western Metropolitan Region since 2006. He was first elected to the Legislative Council in 2006 and re-elected in 2010 and 2014.<ref name=parlbio/> As of November 2014, Finn serves as Member for Western Metropolitan Region alongside [[Cesar Melhem]] and [[Khalil Eideh]] from the [[Australian Labor Party (Victorian Branch)|Labor Party]], [[Colleen Hartland]] from the [[Australian Greens Victoria|Greens]] and [[Rachel Carling-Jenkins]] from the [[Australian Conservatives]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vec.vic.gov.au/Results/State2014/WesternMetropolitanRegion.html|title=State Election 2014: Western Metropolitan Region results summary - Victorian Electoral Commission|work=vec.vic.gov.au}}</ref>\n\nDuring the period of the [[Ted Baillieu|Baillieu]] and [[Denis Napthine|Napthine]] governments, Finn served as Chairman of the [[Parliament of Victoria|Victorian Parliament's]] Electoral Matters Committee.<ref>http://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/images/stories/Media_Release_Final_EMC.pdf</ref>\n\t \nFinn currently serves on the [[Coalition (Australia)|Coalition]] frontbench as the Shadow Parliamentary Secretary for [[autism spectrum disorder]], Shadow Parliamentary Secretary for Electoral Integrity and Shadow Parliamentary Secretary for Melbourne's West.<ref name=parlbio/>\n\nIn 2018 Finn was involved in a controversy where he returned to vote on a bill despite having been granted a \u2018pair\u2019 to be absent from voting due to religious observation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-04-02/victorian-liberals-condemned-by-labor-over-pairing-betrayal/9610358?pfmredir=sm|title=Victorians 'betrayed' over Liberals pairing controversy, Acting Premier says}}</ref>\n\n==Views==\nFinn has drawn controversy for his political views. He has criticised [[Abortion in Australia|abortion]] and [[women's rights]], and been rebuked for his remarks that rape victims should not be allowed an abortion; former [[Premier of Victoria|Premier]] [[Denis Napthine]], who like Finn voted against the 2008 abortion bill,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.prolife.org.au/election/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-03-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150331121712/http://www.prolife.org.au/election/ |archivedate=31 March 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> called Finn's views \"inappropriate.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-03-18/victorian-liberal-mp-says-no-abortions-for-rape-victims/5328448|title=Victorian Liberal MP Bernie Finn says no abortions for rape victims|work=ABC News|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|date=18 Mar 2014|author=Alison Savage}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theage.com.au/victoria/state-mp-bernie-finn-says-there-is-no-acceptable-reason-for-abortion-20140318-34z33.html|title=State MP Bernie Finn says there is no acceptable reason for abortion|date=18 March 2014|author=Josh Gordon and Henrietta Cook|work=[[The Age]]|publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]}}</ref> Finn is a strong opponent of [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Australia|same sex marriage]], [[LGBT adoption and parenting in Australia|adoption]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.3aw.com.au/blogs/neil-mitchell-blog/should-gay-couples-be-able-to-adopt/20140527-3910w.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140729160949/http://www.3aw.com.au/blogs/neil-mitchell-blog/should-gay-couples-be-able-to-adopt/20140527-3910w.html|archivedate=29 July 2014|date=27 May 2014|title=Should gay couples be able to adopt?|quote=Liberal MP Bernie Finn has sparked fierce debate about same-sex couples adopting children after posting controversial anti gay-adoption comments on his Facebook page. Last week, state Labor voted in favour of changing the law, which could pave the way for homosexual couples to adopt if Daniel Andrews wins November's election.However, Mr Finn, MP for the Western Metropolitan Region, who is a Richmond supporter, said he'd join the Collingwood cheer squad before he'd ever support gay adoption, while in another post he asked for \"proof\" that having two mothers or two fathers wouldn't hurt children. Labor today lashed out at Mr Finn, saying the outspoken MP has offended hundreds of loving parents.|work=3AW Mornings}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.starobserver.com.au/news/local-news/victoria-news/calls-for-premier-napthine-to-condemn-mp-over-same-sex-adoption-remarks/123518|title=Calls for Premier Napthine to condemn MP over same-sex adoption remarks|work=Star Observer|date=29 May 2014|author=Benjamin Riley}}</ref> and [[in vitro fertilisation|IVF]]. Finn suggested during the 2012 Australian Open that some gay activists had \"embarked on a program of rainbow fascism.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://global.christianpost.com/news/teenage-tennis-star-denies-making-gay-protest-at-australian-open-67425/|title=Teenage Tennis Star Denies Making Gay Protest at Australian Open|author=Benge Nsenduluka|date=18 January 2012|work=[[Christian Post]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.starobserver.com.au/news/liberal-mp-hits-out-at-%E2%80%98rainbow-fascists%E2%80%99/69546|title=Liberal MP hits out at \u2018rainbow fascists\u2019|work=Star Observer|date=16 Jan 2012|author=Andie Noonan}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/national-affairs/mp-slams-open-rainbow-fascism/story-fn59niix-1226246809149|title=MP slams Open 'rainbow fascism' over Margaret Court|work=The Australian|date=18 Jan 2012|author=Chip Le Grand}}</ref>\n\nFinn was a critic of the federal government's [[Carbon pricing in Australia|carbon pricing scheme]], stating in the Victorian Parliament in 2013 that \"there has been no global warming for 17 years\". He has attacked the climate change documentary ''[[An Inconvenient Truth]]'', as well as reports on the subject in the British newspaper ''[[The Guardian]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/images/stories/daily-hansard/Council_2013/Council_Daily_Extract_Wednesday_11_December_2013_from_Book_17.pdf|publisher=PARLIAMENT OF VICTORIA|title=PARLIAMENTARY DEBATES (HANSARD)|date=11 December 2013}}</ref> He has claimed that [[global warming]] is an invention of the \"international left\", suggesting that \"it raised a few dollars and promoted its own political interests. It came up with a thing called global warming\", which he labelled \"nonsense\". He went on to say that \"we have to come to a conclusion that climate change is not so much a scientific thing as it is a political thing\". Finn also told Parliament that \"This is a con; the whole thing is a con. Today we are in the Parliament of Victoria wasting our time on something that is largely an invention of the left\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.berniefinn.com/news.php?article=891|title=Bernie Finn MP|work=berniefinn.com}}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nFinn supports reintroducing [[Capital punishment in Australia|capital punishment]]. In 2018, Finn said he believes \"if two or three drug lords were executed, others would get the message. They should be disqualified from breathing the same oxygen that we do.\"<ref>https://au.news.yahoo.com/mp-bernie-finn-calls-to-bring-back-death-penalty-for-drug-dealers-39823625.html</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBefore entering Parliamen was a small businessman, broadcaster and a media and ministerial adviser to [[Chris Pearce (politician)|Chris Pearce]].<ref name=\"parlbio\"/> Heed with six children.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bernard (Bernie) Finn|url=http://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/members/details/28-mr-bernard-finn|website=Parliament.vic.gov.au|publisher=Parliament of Victoria|accessdate=3 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.berniefinn.com}}\n* [http://www.abc.net.au/mediawatch/transcripts/1427_pm.pdf Bernie Finn and his \"crazy mates\" named in leaked tape]\n* [http://www.theage.com.au/victoria/state-mp-bernie-finn-says-there-is-no-acceptable-reason-for-abortion-20140318-34z33.html State MP Bernie Finn says there is no acceptable reason for abortion]\n* [http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/liberal-mp-bernie-finn-wants-death-penalty-for-drug-lords/story-e6frf7kx-1226003939525 Liberal MP Bernie Finn wants death penalty for drug lords but victims say don't execute]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20170113062603/http://vicvote.review/council/members/Bernie%20Finn.html Parliamentary voting record of Bernie Finn at Victorian Parliament Tracker]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|au-vic-la}}\n{{succession box | title=Member for [[Electoral district of Tullamarine|Tullamarine]] | before='''Seat created''' | after=[[Liz Beattie]] | years=1992&ndash;1999}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{VicCurrentMLCs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Finn, Bernie}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Australian monarchists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Victorian Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:Members of the Victorian Legislative Council]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party of Australia members of the Parliament of Victoria]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the football player|Bernie Finn (American football)}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2014}}\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name               = Bernie Finn\n|honorific-suffix   = MLC\n|image              = \n|birth_name         = Bernard Thomas Christopher Finn\n|birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1961|4|14|df=y}}\n|birth_place        = \n|office1            = Member of the [[Victorian Legislative Council]]\n|party              = [[Liberal Party of Australia (Victorian Division)|Liberal Party]]\n|occupation         = Businessman, broadcaster, ministerial advisor\n<!-- Deprecated parameter |religion = [[Roman Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]] -->\n|term_start1        = 25 November 2006\n|website            = {{url|http://www.berniefinn.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Bernard (Bernie) Thomas Christopher Finn''' (born 14 April 1961) is a member of the [[Victorian Legislative Council]] representing the [[Western Metropolitan Region]] since the election of November 2006.<ref name=parlbio>{{cite web |title=Bernie Finn (Western Metropolitan)|work=Members Information |publisher=[[Parliament of Victoria]]|url=http://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/members/id/28|accessdate=20 December 2011}}</ref> He was previously the member for the [[electoral district of Tullamarine]] in the [[Victorian Legislative Assembly]] from October 1992 until September 1999.\n\n==Political career==\nFinn was originally a member of the [[Democratic Labour Party (Australia)|Democratic Labor Party]] (DLP). In 1980, aged 19, he was the DLP candidate for the federal seat of [[Division of Corangamite|Corangamite]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://psephos.adam-carr.net/countries/a/australia/1980/1980repsvic.txt|title=1980 Election|website=Psephos|last=Carr|first=Adam}}</ref> Soon after, he left the DLP and joined the [[Liberal Party of Australia (Victorian Division)|Liberal Party]]. In 1983 he was the Liberal candidate for the seat of [[Division of Burke (1969\u20132004)|Burke]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://psephos.adam-carr.net/countries/a/australia/1983/1983repsvic.txt|title=1983 Election|last=Carr|first=Adam|website=Psephos}}</ref>\n\nFinn was the Member for the District of Tullamarine from 1992 until 1999 when he lost power in the Steve Bracks led landslide victory over the Kennett Liberal Government.\n\nFinn has been the number one candidate on the Liberal Party of Australia ticket in the Western Metropolitan Region since 2006. He was first elected to the Legislative Council in 2006 and re-elected in 2010 and 2014.<ref name=parlbio/> As of November 2014, Finn serves as Member for Western Metropolitan Region alongside [[Cesar Melhem]] and [[Khalil Eideh]] from the [[Australian Labor Party (Victorian Branch)|Labor Party]], [[Colleen Hartland]] from the [[Australian Greens Victoria|Greens]] and [[Rachel Carling-Jenkins]] from the [[Australian Conservatives]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vec.vic.gov.au/Results/State2014/WesternMetropolitanRegion.html|title=State Election 2014: Western Metropolitan Region results summary - Victorian Electoral Commission|work=vec.vic.gov.au}}</ref>\n\nDuring the period of the [[Ted Baillieu|Baillieu]] and [[Denis Napthine|Napthine]] governments, Finn served as Chairman of the [[Parliament of Victoria|Victorian Parliament's]] Electoral Matters Committee.<ref>http://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/images/stories/Media_Release_Final_EMC.pdf</ref>\n\t \nFinn currently serves on the [[Coalition (Australia)|Coalition]] frontbench as the Shadow Parliamentary Secretary for [[autism spectrum disorder]], Shadow Parliamentary Secretary for Electoral Integrity and Shadow Parliamentary Secretary for Melbourne's West.<ref name=parlbio/>\n\nIn 2018 Finn was involved in a controversy where he returned to vote on a bill despite having been granted a \u2018pair\u2019 to be absent from voting due to religious observation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-04-02/victorian-liberals-condemned-by-labor-over-pairing-betrayal/9610358?pfmredir=sm|title=Victorians 'betrayed' over Liberals pairing controversy, Acting Premier says}}</ref>\n\n==Views==\nFinn has drawn controversy for his political views. He has criticised [[Abortion in Australia|abortion]] and [[women's rights]], and been rebuked for his remarks that rape victims should not be allowed an abortion; former [[Premier of Victoria|Premier]] [[Denis Napthine]], who like Finn voted against the 2008 abortion bill,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.prolife.org.au/election/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-03-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150331121712/http://www.prolife.org.au/election/ |archivedate=31 March 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> called Finn's views \"inappropriate.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-03-18/victorian-liberal-mp-says-no-abortions-for-rape-victims/5328448|title=Victorian Liberal MP Bernie Finn says no abortions for rape victims|work=ABC News|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|date=18 Mar 2014|author=Alison Savage}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theage.com.au/victoria/state-mp-bernie-finn-says-there-is-no-acceptable-reason-for-abortion-20140318-34z33.html|title=State MP Bernie Finn says there is no acceptable reason for abortion|date=18 March 2014|author=Josh Gordon and Henrietta Cook|work=[[The Age]]|publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]}}</ref> Finn is a strong opponent of [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Australia|same sex marriage]], [[LGBT adoption and parenting in Australia|adoption]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.3aw.com.au/blogs/neil-mitchell-blog/should-gay-couples-be-able-to-adopt/20140527-3910w.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140729160949/http://www.3aw.com.au/blogs/neil-mitchell-blog/should-gay-couples-be-able-to-adopt/20140527-3910w.html|archivedate=29 July 2014|date=27 May 2014|title=Should gay couples be able to adopt?|quote=Liberal MP Bernie Finn has sparked fierce debate about same-sex couples adopting children after posting controversial anti gay-adoption comments on his Facebook page. Last week, state Labor voted in favour of changing the law, which could pave the way for homosexual couples to adopt if Daniel Andrews wins November's election.However, Mr Finn, MP for the Western Metropolitan Region, who is a Richmond supporter, said he'd join the Collingwood cheer squad before he'd ever support gay adoption, while in another post he asked for \"proof\" that having two mothers or two fathers wouldn't hurt children. Labor today lashed out at Mr Finn, saying the outspoken MP has offended hundreds of loving parents.|work=3AW Mornings}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.starobserver.com.au/news/local-news/victoria-news/calls-for-premier-napthine-to-condemn-mp-over-same-sex-adoption-remarks/123518|title=Calls for Premier Napthine to condemn MP over same-sex adoption remarks|work=Star Observer|date=29 May 2014|author=Benjamin Riley}}</ref> and [[in vitro fertilisation|IVF]]. Finn suggested during the 2012 Australian Open that some gay activists had \"embarked on a program of rainbow fascism.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://global.christianpost.com/news/teenage-tennis-star-denies-making-gay-protest-at-australian-open-67425/|title=Teenage Tennis Star Denies Making Gay Protest at Australian Open|author=Benge Nsenduluka|date=18 January 2012|work=[[Christian Post]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.starobserver.com.au/news/liberal-mp-hits-out-at-%E2%80%98rainbow-fascists%E2%80%99/69546|title=Liberal MP hits out at \u2018rainbow fascists\u2019|work=Star Observer|date=16 Jan 2012|author=Andie Noonan}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/national-affairs/mp-slams-open-rainbow-fascism/story-fn59niix-1226246809149|title=MP slams Open 'rainbow fascism' over Margaret Court|work=The Australian|date=18 Jan 2012|author=Chip Le Grand}}</ref>\n\nFinn was a critic of the federal government's [[Carbon pricing in Australia|carbon pricing scheme]], stating in the Victorian Parliament in 2013 that \"there has been no global warming for 17 years\". He has attacked the climate change documentary ''[[An Inconvenient Truth]]'', as well as reports on the subject in the British newspaper ''[[The Guardian]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/images/stories/daily-hansard/Council_2013/Council_Daily_Extract_Wednesday_11_December_2013_from_Book_17.pdf|publisher=PARLIAMENT OF VICTORIA|title=PARLIAMENTARY DEBATES (HANSARD)|date=11 December 2013}}</ref> He has claimed that [[global warming]] is an invention of the \"international left\", suggesting that \"it raised a few dollars and promoted its own political interests. It came up with a thing called global warming\", which he labelled \"nonsense\". He went on to say that \"we have to come to a conclusion that climate change is not so much a scientific thing as it is a political thing\". Finn also told Parliament that \"This is a con; the whole thing is a con. Today we are in the Parliament of Victoria wasting our time on something that is largely an invention of the left\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.berniefinn.com/news.php?article=891|title=Bernie Finn MP|work=berniefinn.com}}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nFinn supports reintroducing [[Capital punishment in Australia|capital punishment]]. In 2018, Finn said he believes \"if two or three drug lords were executed, others would get the message. They should be disqualified from breathing the same oxygen that we do.\"<ref>https://au.news.yahoo.com/mp-bernie-finn-calls-to-bring-back-death-penalty-for-drug-dealers-39823625.html</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBefore entering Parliament, Finn was a small businessman, broadcaster and a media and ministerial adviser to [[Chris Pearce (politician)|Chris Pearce]].<ref name=\"parlbio\"/> He is married with six children.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bernard (Bernie) Finn|url=http://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/members/details/28-mr-bernard-finn|website=Parliament.vic.gov.au|publisher=Parliament of Victoria|accessdate=3 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.berniefinn.com}}\n* [http://www.abc.net.au/mediawatch/transcripts/1427_pm.pdf Bernie Finn and his \"crazy mates\" named in leaked tape]\n* [http://www.theage.com.au/victoria/state-mp-bernie-finn-says-there-is-no-acceptable-reason-for-abortion-20140318-34z33.html State MP Bernie Finn says there is no acceptable reason for abortion]\n* [http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/liberal-mp-bernie-finn-wants-death-penalty-for-drug-lords/story-e6frf7kx-1226003939525 Liberal MP Bernie Finn wants death penalty for drug lords but victims say don't execute]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20170113062603/http://vicvote.review/council/members/Bernie%20Finn.html Parliamentary voting record of Bernie Finn at Victorian Parliament Tracker]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|au-vic-la}}\n{{succession box | title=Member for [[Electoral district of Tullamarine|Tullamarine]] | before='''Seat created''' | after=[[Liz Beattie]] | years=1992&ndash;1999}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{VicCurrentMLCs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Finn, Bernie}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Australian monarchists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Victorian Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:Members of the Victorian Legislative Council]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party of Australia members of the Parliament of Victoria]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian politicians]]\n", "name_user": "2607:fea8:a3e0:1943:3455:6165:c718:d602", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bernie_Finn"}
{"title_page": "Margaret Peterson Haddix", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2013}}\n{{infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| image = Margaret Peterson Haddix.jpg\n| imagesize = \n| alp = \n| caption = \n| pseudonym = \n| birth_name = Margaret Peterson\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1964|4|9}}\n| birth_place = [[Washington Court House, Ohio]], United States\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| resting_place = \n| occupation = Author\n| language = \n| nationality = American\n| ethnicity = \n| citizenship = American\n| education = [[Miami University]]\n| alma_mater = \n| period = \n| genre = [[Young adult fiction]]\n| subject = Reading\n| movement = \n| notableworks = {{plainlist|\n* [[The Missing (novel series)|''The Missing'' series]]\n* [[Shadow Children (series)|''Shadow Children'' series]]\n}}\n| awards = \n| spouse = Doug Haddix\n| partner(s) = \n| children = 2\n| relative(s) = \n| signature = \n| signature_alt = \n| website = {{URL|haddixbooks.com}}\n| portaldisp = \n}}\n\n'''Margaret Peterson Haddix''' (born April 9, 1964) is an American writer known best for the two children's series, [[Shadow Children (series)|''Shadow Children'']] (1998\u20132006) and [[The Missing (novel series)|''The Missing'']] (2008\u20132015). She also wrote the tenth volume in ''[[The 39 Clues]]'', published by [[Scholastic Corporation|Scholastic]].<ref name=\"CNNM 10th\">{{cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/news/newsfeeds/articles/marketwire/0604153.htm|title=The 39 Clues. One Ultimate Challenge. Who Will Succeed?|date=April 5, 2010|work=CNN Money|publisher=[[Cable News Network]]|accessdate=April 6, 2010}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nHaddix grew up on a farm about halfway between two small towns: Washington Court House, Ohio, and [[Sabina, Ohio]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=http://haddixbooks.com/about/bio/|title=About the Author \u2013 Margaret Peterson Haddix|website=haddixbooks.com|access-date=2018-03-03}}</ref> Her family was predominantly farmers and she grew up in a family of voracious readers. Some of her favorite books growing up included  E.L. Konigsburg books, Harriet the Spy, Anne of Green Gables, Louisa May Alcott\u2019s Little Women, Anne Frank, Rebecca of Sunnybrook Farm, and The Little Princess. \n\nShe graduated from [[Miami University]] in [[Oxford, Ohio]] with degrees in English/journalism, English/Creative writing, and History. While in college, Haddix worked a series of jobs. She was an assistant cook at a 4-H camp, but almost every other job has been related to writing.  During college, she worked on the school newspaper and had summer internships at newspapers in Urbana, Ohio; Charlotte, North Carolina; and Indianapolis, Indiana.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nHaddix chose to pursue fiction writing after her husband, Doug, became a news reporter, because she did not want to be his employee.<ref name=\"famousauthors.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.famousauthors.org/margaret-peterson-haddix|title=Margaret Peterson Haddix - Biography, Books and Facts|website=www.famousauthors.org|accessdate=September 1, 2018}}</ref> Her previous work as a reporter inspired her to write fiction. After documenting a wide variety of topics, she wanted to create her own plots and characters. Haddix experienced a long period of having her writing rejected by publishers before her first two books were accepted in 1995 and 1996. Her first book was ''[[Running Out of Time (Haddix novel)|Running Out of Time]]'', published when Haddix was pregnant with her second child, and her first child was one and a half years old.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://haddixbooks.com/about/bio/|title=About the Author \u2013 Margaret Peterson Haddix|website=haddixbooks.com|accessdate=September 1, 2018}}</ref> Her second book, ''[[Don't You Dare Read This, Mrs. Dunphrey]]'', followed shortly after. ''The Summer of Broken Things'', written in 2018, is Haddix\u2019s most recently published stand-alone book.<ref name=\"famousauthors.org\"/>\n\nHaddix has written more than 30 books for children and teenagers, including ''Running Out of Time'', ''Don't You Dare Read This, Mrs. Dunphrey'', ''[[Leaving Fishers]]'', ''[[Just Ella]]'', ''[[Turnabout (Haddix novel)|Turnabout]]'', ''Takeoffs and Landings'', ''The Girl with 500 Middle Names'', ''[[Because of Anya]]'', ''[[Escape from Memory]]'', ''Say What?'', ''The House on the Gulf'', ''[[Double Identity (Haddix novel)|Double Identity]]'', ''Dexter the Tough'', ''[[Uprising (novel)|Uprising]]'', ''Palace of Mirrors'', ''[[Claim to Fame]]'', ''The Always War'', ''Game Changer'', the [[Shadow Children]] series, and the Missing series. She also wrote ''[[Into the Gauntlet]]'', book 10 in ''[[The 39 Clues|39 Clues]]'' series. Her books have made [[New York Times Best Seller|''New York Times'' Best Seller]] lists and [[American Library Association]] (ALA) annual book lists and they have won the International Reading Association's Children's Book Award and more than a dozen state reader's choice awards.<ref name=biog/>\n\nThe ''New York Times''\u2019 best-selling author currently lives in [[Columbus, Ohio]] with her husband, Doug, and their two children, Meredith and Connor.<ref name=\"famousauthors.org\"/>\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n=== [[Shadow Children]] series ===\n* ''[[Among the Hidden]]'' (1998)\n* ''[[Among the Impostors]]'' (2001)\n* ''[[Among the Betrayed]]'' (2002)\n* ''[[Among the Barons]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[Among the Brave]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[Among the Enemy]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[Among the Free]]'' (2006)\n\n=== The Palace Chronicles ===\n* ''[[Just Ella]]'' (1999)\n* ''[[Just Ella#Palace of Mirrors|Palace of Mirrors]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[Just Ella#Palace of Lies|Palace of Lies]]'' (2015)\n\n=== [[The Missing (novel series)|The Missing]] series ===\n* ''[[The Missing (novel series)#Found|Found]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[The Missing (novel series)#Sent|Sent]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[The Missing (novel series)#Sabotaged|Sabotaged]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[The Missing (novel series)#Torn|Torn]]'' (2011)\n* ''[[The Missing (novel series)#Caught|Caught]]'' (2012)\n* ''[[The Missing (novel series)#Shorts|Sought]]'' (E-book short story, 2013)\n* ''[[The Missing (novel series)#Risked|Risked]]'' (2013)\n* ''[[The Missing (novel series)#Shorts|Rescued]]'' (E-book short story, 2014)\n* ''[[The Missing (novel series)#Revealed|Revealed]]'' (2014)\n* ''[[The Missing (novel series)#Redeemed|Redeemed]]'' (2015)\n\n=== [[The 39 Clues]] series ===\n* ''[[Into the Gauntlet]]'' ([[Scholastic Publishing]], 2010), Book 10 in the ''[[The 39 Clues|The 39 Clues series]]''\n\n=== Children of Exile series ===\n* ''Children of Exile'' (2016)\n* ''Children of Refuge'' (2017)\n* ''Children of Jubilee'' (2018)\n\n=== Under Their Skin series ===\n* ''Under Their Skin'' (2016)\n* ''In Over Their Heads'' (2017)\n\n=== The Greystone Secrets series ===\n* ''The Strangers'' (2019)\n* ''The Deceivers'' (2020)\n\n=== Stand-alone novels ===\n* ''[[Running Out of Time (Haddix novel)|Running Out of Time]]'' (1995)\n* ''[[Don't You Dare Read This, Mrs. Dunphrey]]'' (1996)\n* ''[[Leaving Fishers]]'' (1997)\n* ''[[Turnabout (Haddix novel)|Turnabout]]'' (2000)\n* ''Takeoffs and Landings'' (2001)\n* ''The Girl With 500 Middle Names'' (2001)\n* ''[[Because of Anya]]'' (2002)\n* ''[[Escape from Memory]]'' (2003)\n* ''Say What?'' (2004)\n* ''The House on the Gulf'' (2004)\n* ''[[Double Identity (Haddix novel)|Double Identity]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[Uprising (novel)|Uprising]]'' (2007)\n* ''Dexter the Tough'' (2007)\n* ''[[Claim to Fame]]'' (2009)\n* ''The Always War'' (2011)\n* ''Game Changer'' (2012)\n* ''Full Ride'' (2013)\n* ''The Summer of Broken Things'' (2018)\n\n==Awards==\nHaddix has received the [[International Reading Association]] Children's Book Award, Champions league, some ALA listings on [[Best Books for Young Adults]] and Quick Picks for Reluctant Young Adult Readers, The National Kids Award, and readers' choice lists in more than 29 states.<ref name=\"CNNM 10th\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist |25em |refs=\n<ref name=biog>\n[http://www.haddixbooks.com/smallbio.html \"Biography (short version)\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004212847/http://www.haddixbooks.com/smallbio.html |date=October 4, 2013 }}. Margaret Peterson Haddix (''haddixbooks.com'').</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Library resources box|by=yes|lcheading= Haddix, Margaret Peterson}}\n* {{official website}}\n* [http://layla.miltsov.org/reviews/haddix Reviews of her books]\n* {{isfdb name|3125}}\n* {{LCAuth|n95026916|Margaret Peterson Haddix|50|}}\n\n{{Portal|Children and Young Adult Literature}}\n\n{{Margaret Haddix}}\n{{39 Clues}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Haddix, Margaret Peterson}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:American children's writers]]\n[[Category:American science fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American women novelists]]\n[[Category:American young adult novelists]]\n[[Category:Novelists from Ohio]]\n[[Category:Miami University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Washington Court House, Ohio]]\n[[Category:American women children's writers]]\n[[Category:Women science fiction and fantasy writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:Women writers of young adult literature]]\n[[Category:Writers of young adult science fiction]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2013}}\n{{infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| image = Margaret Peterson Haddix.jpg\n| imagesize = \n| alp = \n| caption = \n| pseudonym = \n| birth_name = Margaret Peterson\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1964|4|9}}\n| birth_place = [[Washington Court House, Ohio]], United States\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| resting_place = \n| occupation = Author\n| language = \n| nationality = American\n| ethnicity = \n| citizenship = American\n| education = [[Miami University]]\n| alma_mater = \n| period = \n| genre = [[Young adult fiction]]\n| subject = Reading\n| movement = \n| notableworks = {{plainlist|\n* [[The Missing (novel series)|''The Missing'' series]]\n* [[Shadow Children (series)|''Shadow Children'' series]]\n}}\n| awards = \n| spouse = Doug Haddix\n| partner(s) = \n| children = 2\n| relative(s) = \n| signature = \n| signature_alt = \n| website = {{URL|haddixbooks.com}}\n| portaldisp = \n}}\n\n'''Margaret Peterson Haddix''' (born April 9, 1964) is an American writer known best for the two children's series, [[Shadow Children (series)|''Shadow Children'']] (1998\u20132006) and [[The Missing (novel series)|''The Missing'']] (2008\u20132015). She also wrote the tenth volume in ''[[The 39 Clues]]'', published by [[Scholastic Corporation|Scholastic]].<ref name=\"CNNM 10th\">{{cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/news/newsfeeds/articles/marketwire/0604153.htm|title=The 39 Clues. One Ultimate Challenge. Who Will Succeed?|date=April 5, 2010|work=CNN Money|publisher=[[Cable News Network]]|accessdate=April 6, 2010}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nHaddix grew up on a farm about halfway between two small towns: Washington Court House, Ohio, and [[Sabina, Ohio]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=http://haddixbooks.com/about/bio/|title=About the Author \u2013 Margaret Peterson Haddix|website=haddixbooks.com|access-date=2018-03-03}}</ref> Her family was predominantly farmers and she grew up in a family of voracious readers. Some of her favorite books growing up included  E.L. Konigsburg books, Harriet the Spy, Anne of Green Gables, Louisa May Alcott\u2019s Little Women, Anne Frank, Rebecca of Sunnybrook Farm, and The Little Princess. \n\nShe graduated from [[Miami University]] in [[Oxford, Ohio]] with degrees in English/journalism, English/Creative writing, and History. While in college, Haddix worked a series of